um channel blockade","Prostaglandin synthesis inhibition","Non-selective serotonin receptor antagonism"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETriptans exert their therapeutic effect through \u003Cstrong\u003Eselective serotonin (5-HT1B/1D) receptor agonism\u003C/strong\u003E. This has two main effects:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVasoconstriction of dilated cranial blood vessels (5/HT1B receptor)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStimulation of 5/HT1D receptors on trigeminal nerves causing inhibition of the release of vasoactive peptides and neurotransmitters that cause pain\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcitonin gene-related peptide antagonism\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of newer anti-migraine medications called gepants. \u003Cstrong\u003EVoltage-gated sodium channel blockade\u003C/strong\u003E is seen with local anaesthetics and some anticonvulsants, whilst \u003Cstrong\u003Eprostaglandin synthesis inhibition\u003C/strong\u003E is how non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs work. \u003Cstrong\u003ENon-selective serotonin receptor antagonism\u003C/strong\u003E would block all serotonin receptors indiscriminately and could worsen migraine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy specifically activating 5-HT1B/1D receptors, triptans target both the vascular and neurogenic components of migraine pathophysiology.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Triptans are selective serotonin (5-HT1B/1D) receptor agonists that cause vasoconstriction of cranial blood vessels.","Triptans reduce neurogenic inflammation and inhibit pain transmission in the trigeminal system.","The therapeutic effects of triptans in migraine are due to both vascular and neural mechanisms."],"references":["Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al. Rang and Dale\u0027s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook (online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from: https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96068"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14798"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96068"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-14T23:32:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-14T23:32:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7489"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114053"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"p